"""
MKT Context Commentary — John chapters 12–13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-john-12-13.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/john.json (philological background)
- data/commentary/jfb/john.json (historical background)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/john.json (existing chs 1–7, for style continuity)

Key decisions in this range:
- "The Evangelist" maintained as the preferred designation for the author
- "The Jewish leaders" for hoi Ioudaioi in political/juridical contexts; "Jewish crowd"
  or "the people" when the referent is the pilgrimage multitude
- Nard (spikenard) identified as imported from the Himalayas — its extreme expense is
  the cultural point, not mere luxury
- Palm branches at 12:13 treated with their Maccabean nationalist freight; not mere
  festive decoration
- The "Greeks" at 12:20 identified as God-fearers attending the Passover festival,
  not diaspora Jews (they approach via Philip, who has a Greek name and is from
  Bethsaida — the bilingual gateway city)
- The divine voice at 12:28 identified as the third such public attestation in
  the Johannine narrative structure (cf. baptism / transfiguration in Synoptics);
  John's version here is unique in being during the public ministry
- Isaiah 53:1 at 12:38 and Isa 6:9-10 at 12:40 treated as a deliberate Isaianic
  doublet — the Evangelist quotes from both halves of Isaiah (Deutero-Isaiah and
  Proto-Isaiah) as a single unified prophetic witness
- Footwashing at 13:1-17 set against the slave/servant context of the Greco-Roman
  triclinium dinner; the act inverts the honor-shame hierarchy of the dining room
- The "new commandment" at 13:34 treated against the background of what makes it
  new — not the command to love (present in Lev 19:18) but the measure ("as I have
  loved you") and the social function (identity marker for the community)
- Judas's exit "and it was night" (13:30) read as the Evangelist's light/darkness
  theological frame, operative since the prologue
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>Bethany sits on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, roughly two miles from Jerusalem — close enough for a day trip but outside the city boundary, which meant Jesus could stay there without sleeping in the crowded festival city itself. The Evangelist locates this scene "six days before the Passover," which places it on a Sunday if the crucifixion falls on Friday. This chronological precision is unusual for the Fourth Gospel and signals that the Passion clock has started. The identification of Bethany as the place where Lazarus was raised anchors the scene in the sign that precipitated the authorities\' decision to kill Jesus (11:53); the dinner is taking place in the shadow of that decision.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The dinner is a formal <em>deipnon</em> — the main evening meal — given "in his honor," indicating Jesus is the guest of distinction. Martha serves (<em>diēkonei</em>, imperfect — she keeps on serving), and Lazarus reclines at table with Jesus. Reclining at table (<em>anakeimenōn</em>) was the posture of free persons at a formal dinner; slaves and servants stood and served. That Lazarus reclines alongside Jesus is a status marker: he is an honored guest, not a dependent. The Evangelist positions this meal as a deliberate counter-scene to the authorities\' death plot — in Bethany, those closest to Jesus gather in solidarity around a common table.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Mary\'s action is a series of calculated reversals of the dinner\'s social codes. Nard (<em>nardos pistikē</em>, "pure nard" or "genuine nard") was imported from the Himalayan foothills of India and was among the most expensive aromatic substances available in the first-century Mediterranean world. The quantity — a Roman pound (<em>litra</em>, roughly twelve ounces) — was extravagant: this was the entirety of the vessel, not a measured portion. Anointing the feet rather than the head further inverts the expected honor gesture: heads were anointed for royal or priestly distinction (cf. 1 Sam 10:1; Ps 23:5); feet were the lowest part of the body. Wiping the feet with her hair compounded the inversion — women in Jewish society kept their hair covered in public, and loosening it was done only in contexts of mourning or intimate privacy. Mary collapses all social distance between herself and Jesus in an act that was simultaneously extravagant, scandalous, and prophetic.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The Evangelist identifies the objector immediately as Judas Iscariot and adds the parenthetical note that he was "later to betray him" — a proleptic identification that frames Judas\'s objection not as principled concern for the poor but as a character disclosure. The reader is being given interpretive guidance: this objection is not neutral. "Iscariot" is most likely a transliteration of <em>ish-Qeriyoth</em>, "man of Kerioth," a Judean village — making Judas the only non-Galilean among the Twelve, a detail that may have carried social significance for a Galilean Jesus movement.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Three hundred denarii represented roughly a year\'s wages for a day-laborer — the sum Judas names reflects actual market knowledge of high-grade imported nard, not hyperbole. The comparison to almsgiving activates a real ethical framework: Jewish piety placed enormous weight on care for the poor (<em>tsedaqah</em>), and distributing a large sum would have been a genuinely honorable act. The objection has the form of a serious moral argument, which is why the disciples are described in the Synoptic versions (Matt 26:8; Mark 14:4) as indignant alongside Judas. The Evangelist removes this sympathetic framing by revealing Judas\'s ulterior motive.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Evangelist\'s aside that Judas controlled the common purse and regularly took from it is the only instance in the Gospels of explicit embezzlement attributed to one of the Twelve. The word translated "took" (<em>ebastazen</em>) can mean "carried" or "stole" — the double meaning is probably intentional. In the ancient world, the manager of a common fund had nearly unlimited practical access to it; written accounting and external oversight were minimal. Judas\'s position gave him both legitimate authority and structural opportunity. The Evangelist presents the betrayal not as an isolated act but as the final escalation of a pattern already established.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Jesus\'s response is elliptical in the Greek: "Leave her alone, that she may keep it for the day of my burial" — or "she has kept it for the day of my burial." The ambiguity matters: either Jesus is saying Mary was saving the nard for a burial anointing all along (whether consciously or not), or he is instructing them to leave her alone because what has just been done functions as a burial anointing. Jewish burial practice involved washing the body and applying aromatic spices to slow decomposition and honor the dead (cf. the spices brought in 19:39–40). Jesus reframes the extravagant act as preparation for what is coming within the week.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The saying "The poor you will always have with you" is a quotation from Deut 15:11 ("For the poor will never cease from the land") — a verse that in context is an argument not for indifference to poverty but for the perpetual obligation of generosity. The full Deuteronomy passage commands: "Therefore I command you, you shall open wide your hand to your brother, to the needy." Jesus is not dismissing concern for the poor; he is invoking the Torah frame that assumes their presence and commands care, while distinguishing a unique and unrepeatable moment from the ongoing obligation. He will not always be present in this way.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The "large crowd of Jews" here is the Passover pilgrimage crowd, not the Jerusalem leadership — hundreds of thousands came to Jerusalem for the festival from across Judea and the diaspora. Lazarus had become a figure of intense public curiosity: a man known to have been four days dead and then raised would have been a singular phenomenon in any setting. The crowd\'s two-fold purpose — to see Jesus and to see Lazarus — highlights how the resurrection sign had made Lazarus himself a living testimony. His presence at the dinner (v. 2) meant that the news of Jesus\'s whereabouts would spread rapidly through the festival crowd.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The decision of the chief priests to kill Lazarus as well as Jesus reveals the political logic of their position. Lazarus was not a teacher or a threat to Roman order; his danger was evidentiary — he was walking, breathing proof that Jesus had raised someone from the dead. Eliminating the evidence was standard political reasoning in a patronage system where maintaining the appearance of authority was essential. The high priestly families (primarily the house of Annas/Caiaphas) controlled the Temple economy and their position depended on Roman confidence; a popular messianic movement backed by miracles endangered both.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The phrase "going over to Jesus and believing in him" uses <em>hypēgon</em> — literally "going away," with the implication of defection from the social and religious network the leaders presided over. Belief in Jesus in this context was not merely a private spiritual decision; it was a public realignment of community loyalty. Those who crossed over faced loss of standing in the synagogue community (cf. 9:22; 12:42) — a significant social cost in a society where religious and economic life were intertwined. The leaders\' loss of constituency to Jesus made Lazarus a political liability.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The pilgrimage crowd (<em>ho ochlos polys</em>, "the great crowd") that went out to meet Jesus had assembled in Jerusalem for Passover — the city\'s population swelled by estimates ranging from a few hundred thousand to over a million pilgrims during major festivals (Josephus, <em>Jewish War</em> 6.9.3, gives a figure of 2.7 million that is likely rhetorical). The crowd "heard that Jesus was on his way to Jerusalem" — word of his presence in Bethany had clearly spread. The movement to go out and meet an arriving dignitary was a formal honor gesture (<em>apantēsis</em>) associated with welcoming a king or military victor.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Palm branches (<em>baia tōn phoinikōn</em>) carried specific political freight by the first century. During the Maccabean revolt (165 BCE), palm fronds were waved when Simon Maccabeus recaptured Jerusalem and purified the Temple (1 Macc 13:51; 2 Macc 10:7) — an event deeply embedded in Jewish collective memory as the last successful liberation from foreign oppression. By waving palms, the crowd was casting Jesus in the role of the liberating king. The cry "Hosanna" (<em>hōsanna</em>) is a transliteration of the Hebrew <em>hoshia-na</em> ("save, please!") from Ps 118:25, a Hallel psalm sung at Passover. "Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord" is Ps 118:26; "Blessed is the King of Israel" is the crowd\'s own addition, making the messianic application explicit.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The finding of a donkey and sitting on it is presented as a fulfillment of Zechariah\'s prophecy (Zech 9:9), though the Evangelist\'s quotation at v. 15 is abbreviated. In the Synoptics, the obtaining of the animal is arranged in advance (Mark 11:1–6); John\'s "found" (<em>heurōn</em>) is simpler and less elaborate. The donkey colt was a specific fulfillment marker that distinguished the entry from the arrival of a military conqueror on horseback; riding a donkey in Zechariah\'s framing signals peace and accessibility rather than military dominance.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Evangelist\'s quotation combines Zeph 3:16 ("Fear not, Daughter Zion") with Zech 9:9 ("your king is coming, seated on a donkey\'s colt"). The Zechariah verse in full reads: "Righteous and victorious is he, humble and riding on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey." By abbreviating, the Evangelist omits the detail of "righteous and victorious" (<em>tsaddiq weno-sha</em>) and focuses on the peaceful, humble mode of arrival. In Zechariah\'s context, this king comes to bring peace to the nations; his rule extends "from sea to sea and from the River to the ends of the earth" (Zech 9:10) — a universal dominion achieved without military force. This framing directly undercuts the crowd\'s nationalist reading of the palm branches.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The disciples\' failure to understand at the time, followed by retrospective comprehension after the resurrection, is a recurring Johannine epistemological pattern (cf. 2:22; 7:39; 20:9). The Evangelist signals that the meaning of Jesus\'s actions was not transparent even to his closest followers during his earthly ministry — understanding required the interpretive framework that only the glorification event (death, resurrection, gift of the Spirit) could provide. This retrospective hermeneutic was well established in Jewish tradition: the prophets themselves did not always understand what they spoke (cf. 1 Pet 1:10–12), and events were interpreted in light of their outcomes.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The crowd "with him when he called Lazarus from the tomb" had been present at a singular event. In the ancient world, eyewitness testimony carried enormous social weight — there was no documentary evidence culture comparable to modernity, and a person who had seen something with their own eyes was the primary vehicle of information. This crowd had not merely heard reports; they had witnessed Lazarus emerge from the tomb. Their testimony, spreading through the pilgrimage crowd, functioned as the proximate cause of the welcoming demonstration: the entry was staged not primarily by Jesus but by the excited circulation of eyewitness accounts.</p>',
    "18": '<p>This verse clarifies the causal chain: the crowd went out because they had heard about the resurrection sign. The sign of Lazarus thus creates the very demonstration that will be used to justify Jesus\'s arrest (11:47–53). The irony that the Evangelist builds here is characteristic: the greatest sign of life generates the conditions for Jesus\'s death. The leaders had reasoned that one man should die for the nation (11:50); the resurrection of one man from death has now made that political calculation unavoidable from their perspective.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The Pharisees\' frustrated remark — "the whole world has gone after him" — is presented as unwitting prophecy. The Greek <em>ho kosmos</em> ("the world") is the Evangelist\'s loaded theological term for humanity in its alienation from God (cf. 1:10; 3:16–17). The Pharisees mean it sarcastically: "everyone is following him." The Evangelist places it immediately before the arrival of "Greeks" (v. 20), making their complaint proleptically true in a way they cannot see. The irony is Johannine through and through: the opponents speak more truly than they know.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The "Greeks" (<em>Hellēnes</em>) at the festival were almost certainly Gentile God-fearers — non-Jews who had attached themselves to Judaism through synagogue attendance, monotheistic belief, and ethical practice without full proselyte conversion (which would require circumcision for men). Such God-fearers are well attested in the first century (cf. Acts 10:2; 13:16; 17:4) and would have been present at Passover as pilgrims to Jerusalem, though they could not enter the inner Temple courts beyond the Court of the Gentiles. Their arrival at the festival seeking Jesus dramatizes the Pharisees\' complaint about "the whole world" going after him and signals that Jesus\'s ministry is at a threshold moment.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The Greeks approach Philip specifically, and Philip\'s Greek name (<em>Philippos</em>, "lover of horses") may signal he was comfortable navigating between Jewish and Gentile social worlds. He was from Bethsaida (1:44), a city near the Decapolis with a mixed population and significant Greek cultural presence. The polite address "Sir" (<em>kyrie</em>) and the simple request "we would like to see Jesus" — the same verb Jesus used in 1:39 ("Come and you will see") — may be the Evangelist\'s subtle invitation to remember that encounter. The request frames the Greeks as genuine seekers rather than hostile observers.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The relay through Philip to Andrew before approaching Jesus reflects the layered mediation typical of patron-client relations in Mediterranean antiquity. One did not approach a person of significance directly; one worked through intermediaries who had established access. Philip and Andrew were the two disciples with Greek names among the Twelve; their consultation may reflect social navigation of who could most appropriately broker the Greeks\' request. Andrew had already functioned as a broker, bringing his brother Peter to Jesus (1:41–42). The Evangelist does not record whether the Greeks ever "see" Jesus in the narrative sense; their arrival triggers the hour-announcement without a direct encounter being described.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Jesus\'s response to the Greeks\' arrival — "The hour has come for the Son of Man to be glorified" — reorients the scene entirely. The phrase "the hour" (<em>hē hōra</em>) has been deferred throughout the Gospel (2:4; 7:30; 8:20: "his hour had not yet come"); now it has arrived. The title "Son of Man" with its Daniel 7 background (a figure given dominion "over all peoples, nations, and languages" — Dan 7:14) is here explicitly linked to glorification. In the Evangelist\'s ironic frame, "glorification" encompasses both the lifting up on the cross and the resurrection-exaltation — the suffering and the triumph are inseparable.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The grain-of-wheat saying draws on agricultural experience that every rural listener would know: a seed planted in the ground appears to be lost, but its death is the necessary condition for multiplication. The saying circulated in various forms in Second Temple Judaism as a way of explaining why righteous suffering could be productive (cf. 4 Ezra 4:28–32, where the same agricultural analogy describes the righteous waiting for their vindication). The double "truly, truly" (<em>amēn amēn</em>) marks this as a pronouncement of special authority. The application Jesus draws is about himself ("it remains only a single seed / if it dies, it bears much fruit"), but v. 25 extends it to all discipleship.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The paradox of loving/hating one\'s life to keep/lose it would have landed as a direct challenge to the dominant values of the honor-shame culture. In the Mediterranean world of the first century, self-preservation, the protection of one\'s honor, and the accumulation of social capital were not merely instincts — they were virtues. A person who failed to protect their family, reputation, and life was considered weak and dishonorable. The contrast between "this world" (<em>kosmos houtos</em>) and "eternal life" (<em>zōē aiōnios</em>) maps the paradox onto a temporal frame: the kind of life worth preserving belongs to the age to come, not to the present social order. The language of "eternal life" carries its Jewish apocalyptic weight here — the resurrection life of the world to come.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The promise that "where I am, my servant also will be" and "my Father will honor the one who serves me" directly inverts the honor-shame calculus of v. 25. In the patronage system, honor came from powerful patrons who publicly recognized their clients. Here the ultimate Patron — the Father — is the one who will honor those who attach themselves to Jesus through service and following. The term "serve" (<em>diakoneō</em>) is the same verb used of Martha in v. 2; the Evangelist may intend a connection between Martha\'s table service and the discipleship Jesus describes here.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The "troubled soul" (<em>tetaraktai hē psychē mou</em>) has a close Johannine parallel in 11:33 and 13:21 — the verb <em>tarassō</em> is used for genuine internal anguish, not merely agitation. This is the closest the Fourth Gospel comes to the Gethsemane tradition preserved in the Synoptics (Mark 14:34: "my soul is deeply grieved, to the point of death"). The rhetorical question "Father, save me from this hour?" is immediately answered and retracted: "No, it was for this very reason I came to this hour." The Evangelist presents Jesus as one who acknowledges the weight of what is coming while maintaining volitional clarity about its necessity. The prayer that follows ("Father, glorify your name") transforms the request: rather than asking for rescue, Jesus asks for the Father\'s glorification through whatever is coming.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A divine voice from heaven (<em>phōnē ek tou ouranou</em>) responding to a human prayer is a recognized category in Jewish tradition: the <em>bat qol</em> ("daughter of a voice"), the lesser divine communication of the post-prophetic age. Rabbinic literature records that when prophecy ceased with Malachi, God continued to communicate through the <em>bat qol</em> in response to righteous acts or prayers. The content of this voice — "I have glorified it, and will glorify it again" — is the third such attestation in the Gospel framework (following the baptismal voice and the Transfiguration voice in the Synoptics; John replaces both with equivalent moments). The past tense ("I have glorified") refers to the signs Jesus has already performed; the future tense points to the crucifixion-resurrection complex.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The crowd\'s divided interpretation — thunder or an angel — reflects the two recognized categories of anomalous aural experience in Jewish tradition. Thunder was associated with divine communication (Exod 19:19; Ps 29); angelic speech was the mechanism of prophetic revelation (Dan 8:16; 9:21). Neither category required or expected an intelligible divine voice addressed to a human being in public, which is why the crowd could not process what they had heard as such. The division of opinion in the crowd echoes the pattern throughout the Gospel (7:43; 9:16; 10:19–21) where Jesus\'s words and actions produce divided responses rather than consensus.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Jesus clarifies that the voice was communicative — intended for the crowd\'s benefit rather than information Jesus himself needed. This echoes the interpretive logic of 11:42, where Jesus prays aloud at Lazarus\'s tomb "for the benefit of the people standing here, that they may believe that you sent me." The Evangelist consistently presents Jesus as the one with unique, unmediated access to the Father, who does not need divine confirmation but who works within the phenomenology of ordinary human religious experience — voices, signs, theophanies — to bring others to belief.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Judgment on this world" (<em>krisis tou kosmou toutou</em>) draws on the Jewish apocalyptic framework in which the present evil age stands under divine condemnation awaiting a final judicial verdict. The language of the "prince of this world" (<em>ho archōn tou kosmou toutou</em>) for Satan or the devil appears in Second Temple Jewish texts (1 Enoch, Testament of the Twelve Patriarchs) and in Pauline letters (2 Cor 4:4: "the god of this age"); it reflects the belief that hostile spiritual powers exercised delegated authority over the present age. The declaration that this ruler "will be driven out" identifies the cross as the decisive cosmic confrontation, not merely a judicial execution.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The phrase "lifted up from the earth" (<em>hypsoō</em>) is the Evangelist\'s characteristic double-meaning term for crucifixion/exaltation (cf. 3:14; 8:28), drawn from the Greek translation of Isa 52:13 ("my servant will be lifted up and exalted"). The promise to "draw all people to myself" (<em>helkō</em> — the same verb used in 6:44 for the Father\'s drawing to the Son) indicates that the crucifixion functions not as defeat but as the mechanism of universal attraction. The "all" (<em>pantas</em>) is significant in context: the Gentile God-fearers (the Greeks of v. 20) are included. The cross functions as the Gentile mission in Johannine theology.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The Evangelist adds his own interpretive gloss, as he does at several key points (cf. 2:21; 7:39; 11:51–52): "He said this to show the kind of death he was going to die." The note clarifies that "lifted up" is not metaphorical elevation but literal crucifixion — the cross was positioned upright, and the condemned were literally raised above the ground. The note closes off a spiritualizing misreading of the lifting-up language and anchors it in the specific Roman execution method.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The crowd\'s challenge — "We have heard from the Law that the Messiah will remain forever" — reflects actual messianic expectation rooted in texts like Ps 89:36 ("his line will continue forever"), Ps 110:4 ("a priest forever"), Dan 7:14 ("his dominion is an everlasting dominion"), and Isa 9:7 ("of the increase of his government there will be no end"). First-century messianic hope was largely oriented toward an enduring, triumphant figure, not a dying one. The crowd\'s question — "Who is this Son of Man?" — reflects genuine puzzlement at the convergence of the death prediction with the messianic claim, not hostility. The two categories they know — Messiah and Son of Man — do not map onto what Jesus is describing.</p>',
    "35": '<p>Jesus\'s response deflects the question about identity into an urgency about opportunity. The "light" (<em>phōs</em>) is available "a little while longer" — a time-limited window that the darkness is about to close. In the context of the Passover week, this is a statement about the next few days. The metaphor of walking in darkness without knowing where you are going draws on a widely shared experience in antiquity: artificial light was expensive, unreliable, and limited in range. Traveling after dark without a lamp was genuinely dangerous. The Evangelist\'s audience would have experienced literal night-blindness in ways modern readers do not.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Children of light" (<em>huioi tou phōtos</em>) is a designation used in the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QM, the War Scroll) for the community of the righteous who will prevail in the final cosmic battle against the "children of darkness." The Qumran community used this light/darkness dualism as a sectarian boundary marker. Jesus\'s use of the same language is either drawing on a shared Jewish apocalyptic vocabulary or (from the Evangelist\'s perspective) correcting it: light-identity comes not through sectarian membership but through belief in the one who is the light (cf. 1:4–9; 8:12). After this declaration, Jesus withdraws and hides, ending the public ministry in the Fourth Gospel.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The summary of unbelief at vv. 37–43 is the Evangelist\'s reflection on why the signs did not produce faith among the leaders. The observation that they "would not believe" (<em>ouk episteuon</em>, imperfect — a sustained, repeated refusal) despite many signs raises the theodicy of failed testimony: what does it mean that the revelation was not received? The Evangelist addresses this by citing two texts from Isaiah, reading the prophet as having foreseen and explained the situation.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Isaiah 53:1 is the opening of what is widely identified as the fourth Servant Song. The verse asks two rhetorical questions: "Who has believed our report?" and "To whom has the arm of the Lord been revealed?" In Isaiah\'s context, the servant\'s exaltation through suffering is incomprehensible to the nations who had despised him. The Evangelist reads this as a prediction of the incomprehension Jesus\'s ministry would produce. The "arm of the Lord" (<em>brachion kyriou</em> in the LXX) is a standard OT designation for God\'s powerful intervention in history (Deut 5:15; Isa 51:9; 52:10). Its non-revelation to unbelievers is the prophetic explanation for the failure of belief.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The Evangelist\'s statement that "they could not believe" shifts the framing from moral failure ("would not") to incapacity ("could not"). The transition into Isa 6:9–10 explains this incapacity not as divine arbitrariness but as the judicial hardening that follows sustained rejection. The pattern in Isaiah is that Pharaoh\'s hardening (Exod 4–14) and the Isaiah commission (Isa 6) both describe God ratifying and intensifying a hardening that was already underway through human refusal. The two Isaiah texts together (53:1 and 6:9–10) frame unbelief as both predicted and judicially confirmed.</p>',
    "40": '<p>Isaiah 6:9–10 is quoted or alluded to in all four Gospels (Mark 4:12; Matt 13:14–15; Luke 8:10; John 12:40) and in Acts 28:26–27 — more NT citations than almost any other OT passage. The LXX version softens the Hebrew: where the Hebrew has God commanding Isaiah to make the people unresponsive, the LXX uses third-person language ("their heart has become fat"). The Evangelist follows neither the Hebrew nor the LXX exactly; his version makes God the direct agent of the blinding and hardening. This is the harshest form of the citation and reflects serious theological wrestling with the failure of the Jewish leadership to respond to Jesus.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The claim that "Isaiah said this because he saw Jesus\' glory" is a remarkable interpretive move. Isaiah\'s vision in Isaiah 6 was of the divine throne room — the Lord (YHWH) high and exalted, attended by seraphim. The Evangelist identifies the glory Isaiah saw as Christ\'s glory, drawing on the high Christology of the prologue (1:14: "we have seen his glory") and implicitly equating the pre-incarnate Word with YHWH enthroned. This hermeneutic — that the OT theophanies were appearances of the pre-incarnate Son — is developed more explicitly in later Christian theology (Justin Martyr, Origen), but the Fourth Gospel plants the seed here.</p>',
    "42": '<p>The category of "secret believers" among the leaders who would not confess openly because of the Pharisees\' threat of exclusion from the synagogue (<em>aposynagōgos</em>) reflects a genuine social reality. The Pharisaic party controlled the synagogue network and could enforce communal discipline; to be expelled was to lose access to community life, business networks, and social support. Nicodemus (3:1–15; 7:50–52) and Joseph of Arimathea (19:38) are the named representatives of this group in the Fourth Gospel. The Evangelist treats their secrecy with neither condemnation nor full approval — they are presented as transitional figures who had genuine faith but had not yet paid the full social cost of discipleship.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"They loved human praise more than praise from God" translates a Greek phrase where "praise" is <em>doxa</em> — the same word rendered "glory" throughout the Gospel. The verse could read: "they loved the glory from human beings more than the glory from God." This frames their failure not as cowardice but as a misoriented glory-seeking — the same failure the Evangelist identified in 5:44 ("How can you believe, when you receive glory from one another and do not seek the glory that comes from God alone?"). The pursuit of honor within the human social system is the structural obstacle to belief throughout the Johannine narrative.</p>',
    "44": '<p>Jesus\'s final public proclamation begins here (vv. 44–50), presented without a narrative introduction — the Evangelist does not say when or where Jesus said this. This rhetorical device suggests a summary declaration rather than a single historical speech. "Whoever believes in me does not believe in me only, but in the one who sent me" is the agency-and-sender Christology that recurs throughout the Gospel: Jesus\'s identity as the sent one means that responses to him are simultaneously responses to the one who sent him (cf. 5:23–24; 13:20; 14:9).</p>',
    "45": '<p>"The one who looks at me is seeing the one who sent me" makes the incarnation the visible form of the invisible God. The Greek <em>theōreō</em> ("looks at," "beholds") carries the sense of sustained, attentive observation rather than a casual glance. In the context of a Jewish monotheism that had a strong tradition of divine invisibility (Exod 33:20; John 1:18), this is a significant claim: the Incarnate Word is the one place where the Father is visible without the violence of direct divine encounter. The claim will be pressed further in 14:9 ("Anyone who has seen me has seen the Father").</p>',
    "46": '<p>The light/darkness motif that has structured the entire Gospel (1:4–5; 3:19–21; 8:12; 9:5; 12:35–36) receives its definitive christological statement here: "I have come into the world as a light, so that no one who believes in me should stay in darkness." The language of coming "into the world" (<em>eis ton kosmon</em>) is the language of the Incarnation (1:9; 3:19; 6:14; 9:39; 10:36; 11:27; 16:28; 18:37) — each reference marks Jesus as the one who crossed the boundary from God\'s realm into the kosmos of alienation. The stated purpose is soteriological: rescue from darkness, not condemnation into it (cf. 3:17).</p>',
    "47": '<p>The statement "I did not come to judge the world, but to save the world" (cf. 3:17) does not contradict the judgment language of vv. 31 and 48; it distinguishes the purpose of the first coming from its judicial effects. The arrival of the light produces judgment as a by-product — those who prefer darkness condemn themselves (3:19–20) — but the intent of the mission is rescue. This distinction between the purpose and the effect of judgment is important for reading the Johannine theology of condemnation: the darkness does not require active condemnation from the outside; it is self-generated by rejection of the light.</p>',
    "48": '<p>"The very words I have spoken will condemn them at the last day" introduces the eschatological judgment frame. The "last day" (<em>hē eschatē hēmera</em>) is a consistent Johannine reference to the resurrection/judgment at the end of the age (6:39–40, 44, 54; 11:24) — the standard Jewish apocalyptic expectation carried forward. The words of Jesus function as the judicial criterion: the question at the final judgment is not what laws were kept but what was done with the words of the Son. This is a Johannine radicalization of the prophetic tradition in which the word spoken by YHWH\'s messenger was itself a dynamic force that would accomplish what it was sent to do (Isa 55:10–11).</p>',
    "49": '<p>The claim that Jesus spoke only what the Father commanded corresponds to the Deuteronomic category of the true prophet: "I will put my words in his mouth, and he will tell them everything I command him" (Deut 18:18). Moses was the paradigmatic figure of this prophetic commission; the expectation of a prophet like Moses (Deut 18:15) was alive in Second Temple Judaism (cf. John 1:21; 6:14; 7:40). The Evangelist frames Jesus not merely as a prophet of this type but as one whose relationship to the Father is unique and constitutive: the words are not transmitted by inspiration but are the direct expression of the Father\'s will through the Son.</p>',
    "50": '<p>"His command leads to eternal life" closes the public ministry section of the Gospel (sometimes called "the Book of Signs," chs 1–12) with the same theme that opened it: eternal life as the goal of the divine mission (3:15–16). The Evangelist ends not with a call to repentance or a warning to the unbelieving crowd but with Jesus\'s own summary of why he spoke — the Father\'s command was for the purpose of eternal life, and Jesus delivered it without alteration. The simplicity of the final statement ("whatever I say is just what the Father has told me to say") forms a deliberate contrast with the complexity of the theological disputes that have filled chapters 5–12.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>The phrase "before the Passover Festival" places the footwashing and farewell discourse a day earlier than the Synoptic accounts, where the Last Supper takes place on the Passover evening itself (Mark 14:12–17). The Fourth Gospel\'s chronology consistently places the crucifixion on the afternoon of Preparation Day (14 Nisan), when the Passover lambs were being slaughtered in the Temple — a deliberate theological alignment that makes Jesus\'s death coincide with the sacrificial lambs\' deaths. The phrase "Jesus knew that the hour had come for him to leave this world" recapitulates 12:23 ("the hour has come") but now adds the destination: return to the Father. The clause "having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end" (<em>eis telos</em>) carries a double meaning — "to the end" as temporal finality and "to the uttermost" as the fullest possible expression of love.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The "evening meal" (<em>deipnon</em>) was the main meal of the day, typically eaten after dark. The Greco-Roman <em>triclinium</em> — the three-sided dining arrangement with couches around three sides of a low table, leaving the fourth side open for servers — was the standard format for a formal dinner in the first century. Guests reclined on their left sides, eating with their right hands, with each person\'s head near the chest of the person behind them on the next couch. This arrangement explains how "the disciple whom Jesus loved" could be reclining at Jesus\'s side (v. 23) — he was on the next couch to Jesus\'s right, with his head near Jesus\'s chest. The Evangelist\'s note that "the devil had already prompted Judas to betray Jesus" introduces the cosmic dimension of the betrayal: Judas is not merely a disgruntled follower but an instrument of the adversary, a motif confirmed in v. 27 when "Satan entered into him."</p>',
    "3": '<p>The verse frames Jesus\'s action with three items of knowledge: the Father had given all things into his hands; he had come from God; he was returning to God. This divine self-consciousness grounds the otherwise incomprehensible act that follows. In the ancient world, a person acted in accordance with their status — the higher one\'s honor, the more expected one\'s display of dignity and the less acceptable one\'s performance of menial service. That the one who knows he holds universal authority and divine origin is about to perform a slave\'s task is the Evangelist\'s way of saying that the act is not ignorance of status but its radical inversion.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Jesus "rose from the meal, laid aside his outer clothing, and wrapped a towel around his waist." The sequence mirrors the action of a household slave preparing to serve: the outer garment (<em>himation</em>) was removed to allow free movement; the towel (<em>lention</em>, a Roman loanword from <em>linteum</em>) was the equipment of a servant. The combination of removing one garment and taking up another — especially as described by the Evangelist with the care of a deliberate, staged action — has been read from early in the tradition as anticipating the passion: the laying aside and taking up again of clothing echoes the laying down and taking up of life in 10:17–18.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Footwashing was a necessary task in a world of sandaled feet, dusty or muddy roads, and reclining table fellowship — feet were the dirtiest part of the body after outdoor travel and needed washing before bringing them to a shared dining surface. The task was ordinarily performed by the lowest-ranking household slave, and in Jewish practice was so menial that the Talmud records a teaching that disciples should not perform it for their rabbi: "All services which a slave performs for his master, a student should perform for his teacher — except for the removal of shoes" (b. Ketubot 96a). The Synoptic Baptist\'s claim that he is not worthy to carry or remove Jesus\'s sandals (Matt 3:11; Mark 1:7; Luke 3:16; John 1:27) uses this same cultural register — the lowest act of servitude as the measure of unworthiness. Jesus performs what even the Baptist would not.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Peter\'s question "Lord, are you going to wash my feet?" uses the emphatic Greek pronoun for "you" (<em>sy mou</em>) and "my feet" — the combination stresses the incongruity of the one acting and the one receiving. Peter\'s instinct here reflects the honor-shame logic of the culture: to allow a superior to perform a servant\'s role would bring shame on both parties. The social script says that someone of Jesus\'s status and authority should not be doing this, and Peter\'s objection is not mere modesty but the culturally coherent response of someone refusing to permit a status violation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Jesus\'s "you do not realize now what I am doing, but later you will understand" is the characteristic Johannine deferral of comprehension until after the resurrection (cf. 2:22; 12:16). The word translated "later" (<em>meta tauta</em>, "after these things") in Jesus\'s mouth is the same phrase the Evangelist uses throughout the Gospel to mark narrative transitions. Peter will understand the footwashing — its meaning as service, humility, and participation in Jesus\'s death and life — only when the Spirit teaches him all things (14:26; 16:13).</p>',
    "8": '<p>Peter\'s absolute refusal — "you shall never wash my feet" uses <em>ou mē</em>, the strongest Greek negation, intensified by "into eternity" (<em>eis ton aiōna</em>) — triggers Jesus\'s equally absolute response: "Unless I wash you, you have no part (<em>meros</em>) with me." The word <em>meros</em> (part, share, portion) is the technical term for one\'s allotted inheritance or participation in an estate — the same concept behind inheritance language in the Psalms and Paul\'s letters. To have "no part" with Jesus is exclusion from what he is and gives. Jesus has converted the footwashing from a social act into a participation metaphor: receiving service from him is the condition of belonging to him.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Peter\'s overcorrection — "not just my feet but my hands and my head as well!" — is entirely characteristic of Peter in the Gospel tradition. Where a yes/no question was intended, Peter responds with maximal enthusiasm. The hands-and-head addition reflects the prescribed parts of the body to be washed in Jewish ritual purification: the <em>tevilah</em> (full-body immersion) involved complete washing; hand-washing (<em>netilat yadayim</em>) was prescribed before meals; head anointing was associated with special honor. Peter is reaching for every category of ritual cleansing available in his mental framework, not understanding that Jesus is not speaking about ritual purity at all.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Jesus\'s answer distinguishes between the one who has bathed (<em>leloumenos</em>, perfect participle — has had a full bath and the result stands) and the one who still needs their feet washed. The image is of someone who has bathed before coming to dinner and only needs the road-dust of the journey removed upon arrival. The distinction maps onto a two-level understanding of cleansing that early Christian tradition would develop: the bath of baptism (complete, unrepeatable) and the ongoing need for repentance and forgiveness in the Christian life. The specific exception — "though not every one of you" — points immediately toward Judas, who has not received what the washing represents despite being present.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The Evangelist\'s aside ("For he knew who was going to betray him") confirms that Jesus\'s caveat about the uncleaned one is intentional and refers to Judas specifically. The knowledge of Judas\'s betrayal is presented throughout ch. 13 as prior, certain, and possessed from the beginning — not discovered gradually. This divine foreknowledge framing is central to the Evangelist\'s presentation: Jesus moves toward his death as one who has full knowledge of what is happening and is choosing to proceed. The betrayal is not a tragedy that overcomes him but the event through which he glorifies the Father.</p>',
    "12": '<p>After washing the feet, Jesus resumes his outer garment (<em>himation</em>) and his place at table — returning to the status position from which he acted. The question "Do you understand what I have done for you?" opens the interpretation that follows in vv. 13–17. In the ancient world, dramatic symbolic acts — especially those involving public role reversals — required verbal interpretation to be correctly understood. Jesus as teacher (<em>didaskalos</em>) provides the interpretive key, which is not merely "serve one another" but something grounded in his own identity as teacher and lord.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Teacher" (<em>didaskalos</em>) and "Lord" (<em>kyrios</em>) are the two highest honorific titles applicable to a Jewish religious leader in the first century. <em>Rabbi</em> (from <em>rav</em>, "great") was the emerging technical term for a recognized teacher with disciples, though its full rabbinic institutionalization came after 70 CE; <em>didaskalos</em> is its Greek equivalent. <em>Kyrios</em> in a Jewish context could range from polite address ("sir") to the divine name translated in the LXX — the Evangelist exploits the ambiguity throughout the Gospel. Jesus affirms the titles without qualification: "rightly so, for that is what I am." The affirmation is not humility but precision: the one who washed their feet was not momentarily lowering himself but revealing the nature of what genuine authority looks like.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The argument in vv. 14–15 is <em>qal wa-homer</em> ("light and heavy"), a standard Jewish interpretive move: if the greater has done X, how much more should the lesser. "Since I, your Lord and Teacher, have washed your feet" — the more honorable party has performed the humble act — "you also should wash one another\'s feet." In some early Christian communities this became a literal liturgical practice (Tertullian, Augustine, and monastic traditions preserved the practice), while others read it figuratively as mutual service. The Fourth Gospel\'s text does not settle the question; Jesus uses it as an illustration of the norm ("as I have done") rather than prescribing a specific repeated ritual.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"I have set you an example" uses the Greek word <em>hypodeigma</em> — a pattern or model held up for imitation. The concept was central to Greek educational philosophy: the teacher embodied the virtue and the student learned by imitation (<em>mimēsis</em>). Aristotle, Plato, and the later philosophical schools all grounded moral formation in imitating exemplary figures. Jesus uses the same pedagogical framework, but the example he sets is not rhetorical excellence or philosophical virtue but servitude. The counter-cultural force of this is precise: in a world where social advancement depended on acquiring clients, patrons, and honor, Jesus designates the slavery posture as the pattern of his community\'s common life.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"No servant is greater than his master, nor is a messenger greater than the one who sent him" is a proverbial saying that appears in slightly different forms across the Gospels (Matt 10:24–25; Luke 6:40). In the context of vv. 1–17, it applies the master-servant logic in both directions: the disciples are not exempt from what the master himself has done, but they are also the authorized agents of the master they represent. The term "messenger" (<em>apostolos</em>) is the word from which "apostle" derives; this is its only occurrence in the Fourth Gospel, applied not as a title but as a functional description of those who are sent on the master\'s business.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"You will be blessed if you do them" — the blessing (<em>makarioi</em>, the same word as the Beatitudes) is conditional on action, not merely knowledge. This distinguishes the Johannine ethics from a purely cognitive gnosis: understanding the footwashing\'s meaning is not sufficient; performance is required. The pattern of knowing-then-doing reflects the Deuteronomic covenant structure, where Israel knows God\'s commands and is called to obedience. The beatitude here is prospective — the blessing is available to those who act on what they now understand.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The citation of Ps 41:9 — "He who shared my bread has turned against me" — activates the Psalmic category of the suffering righteous one betrayed by a close companion. Psalm 41 is a lament of the sick and abandoned, in which the psalmist\'s enemies gloat and even a trusted friend who shared table fellowship turns against him. Table fellowship in the ancient world was a bond of the highest social and moral significance: sharing bread with someone created a reciprocal obligation of loyalty and protection. To betray a table companion was among the most dishonorable acts conceivable in Mediterranean culture — a violation of the friendship (<em>philía</em>) covenant sealed by the shared meal. The Evangelist frames Judas\'s betrayal within this framework: it is not merely treachery but the specific moral horror of betraying someone with whom one has eaten.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"I am telling you now before it happens, so that when it does happen you will believe that I am who I am" — the final phrase in Greek is <em>egō eimi</em>, the "I am" formula used throughout John for both mundane self-identification and the divine name of Exod 3:14. In this context, the predictive foreknowledge itself is the evidence: Jesus knows the betrayal before it happens because his knowledge and identity transcend ordinary human limitations. The structure "I tell you before it happens so that when it happens you will believe" is the Johannine version of the test of true prophecy from Deut 18:22 ("when a prophet speaks in the name of YHWH and the word does not come to pass… that prophet has spoken presumptuously").</p>',
    "20": '<p>The agency chain — "whoever accepts anyone I send accepts me; whoever accepts me accepts the one who sent me" — extends the sender-agent logic of the footwashing discourse into a mission framework. In Semitic agency law (<em>shaliach</em> principle), an authorized representative acted with the full legal standing of the one who sent him; receiving or rejecting the agent was equivalent to receiving or rejecting the principal. The <em>shaliach</em> concept appears in rabbinic literature as "a man\'s agent is as the man himself" (m. Berakhot 5:5). Jesus applies this principle in both directions: his own reception is mediated through those he sends, and his Father\'s reception is mediated through him.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Jesus "was troubled in spirit" (<em>etarachthē tō pneumati</em>) — the same verb <em>tarassō</em> used in 11:33 at the tomb of Lazarus and in 12:27 at the soul-trouble before the passion declaration. The Evangelist uses the verb for genuine anguish, not superficial agitation. The public announcement — "one of you is going to betray me" — would have been shattering in the context of a shared meal. In the honor-shame world, a meal was an occasion of social solidarity; the announcement that a traitor was present violated the protective social space of table fellowship and transformed an intimate gathering into a scene of suspicion and exposure.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The disciples\' reaction — "stared at one another, at a loss to know which of them he meant" — reflects both their shock and the ambiguity of their own self-knowledge. The Greek <em>aporountes</em> ("at a loss," "perplexed") is used in philosophical literature for genuine intellectual aporia — not knowing where to turn. The disciples cannot determine who the betrayer is, which means they have not been paying attention to Judas\'s behavior in the way the Evangelist\'s aside at 12:6 might suggest they should have. The scene is psychologically realistic: in close community, disloyalty often goes undetected until it becomes undeniable.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"The disciple whom Jesus loved" (<em>ho mathētēs hon ēgapa ho Iēsous</em>) appears here for the first time in the Gospel, "reclining next to him" — literally, in his bosom (<em>en tō kolpō</em>, the same phrase used in 1:18 for the Son\'s relationship to the Father). The Beloved Disciple\'s position at the table placed him in the seat of highest honor immediately to Jesus\'s right. In the triclinium arrangement, this was the most intimate position, allowing private conversation. The Beloved Disciple is never identified by name in the Gospel; the function of the anonymity is both to preserve the disciple\'s identity and to create a figure of identification for readers who are invited to occupy the position of the one Jesus loves.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Simon Peter "motions" (<em>neuei</em> — a nod or gesture) to the Beloved Disciple to ask who the betrayer is. Peter\'s position at the table would have been farther from Jesus than the Beloved Disciple\'s, meaning he could not ask directly; he works through the intermediary who has the privileged access position. This spatial logic of the triclinium arrangement makes the scene readable as social reality: not everyone was equally proximate to Jesus at the table, and the Beloved Disciple\'s position gave him access that Peter did not have directly.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Leaning back against Jesus" — the Greek describes the Beloved Disciple turning slightly toward Jesus on the couch while reclining. The intimacy of the posture is physical as well as relational. The question "Lord, who is it?" is whispered, clearly, since the rest of the company does not hear the answer. The scene illustrates how the Fourth Gospel constructs multiple levels of disclosure: Jesus reveals the betrayer to the Beloved Disciple in a private exchange within the public meal — a layer of inner knowledge available to those closest to him that bypasses the larger group.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The dipping of a piece of bread in a communal dish and handing it to another person was a specific gesture of honor and favor at a formal dinner. The guest of honor might offer this to a particularly favored companion; to receive it was to be elevated in the eyes of those present. The meal\'s conventions thus made the identification of the betrayer through the bread dipping — an act of apparent favor — carry devastating irony. Jesus hands a gesture of honor to the one who is about to betray him, and the act of betrayal is masked by the form of favor. The MKT note that "dipping the piece of bread" activates the Ps 41:9 background already cited in v. 18.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"As soon as Judas took the bread, Satan entered into him." The language of Satanic possession or prompting is the Evangelist\'s way of indicating that the act transcends ordinary human motivation — it is the Adversary\'s work, not merely a mercenary decision. Second Temple Judaism\'s developing demonology included the belief that the <em>yetzer ha-ra</em> (evil inclination) could be manipulated by hostile spiritual powers; the figure of the Accuser/Adversary (Hebrew <em>ha-satan</em>) in Job 1–2 and Zechariah 3 had by the first century become associated with cosmic opposition to God\'s purposes. The phrase "What you are about to do, do quickly" is neither permission nor command; it is Jesus\'s assertion of temporal control even over the event that seems most to undo him.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The other disciples do not understand "why Jesus said this to him" — they did not hear or register the exchange at v. 25–26. This is consistent with the private nature of the revelation: the Beloved Disciple and Peter know, but the rest of the company remain unaware. The Evangelist emphasizes the incomprehension of the wider circle to underscore that what is happening is operating at a level of meaning that the ordinary social actors cannot access. The betrayal is embedded within the meal\'s social conventions so seamlessly that it is invisible to most participants.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The two guesses about why Jesus told Judas to "do it quickly" both work within the Passover festival context: purchasing provisions for the multi-day celebration was a legitimate urgent task, and last-minute charitable donations before the festival were an established pious practice (the poor received special consideration during Passover, when all Israel was to remember its slavery and liberation). Both guesses reveal that the disciples understood Judas\'s role as treasurer and assumed a practical interpretation of Jesus\'s words. They have no category for what is actually happening.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"As soon as Judas had taken the bread, he went out. And it was night." The Evangelist\'s final notation — "it was night" — is both factual and theological. Literally, the farewell discourse took place after dark; figuratively, Judas\'s exit is the entry of darkness into the narrative. The light/darkness motif that has structured the Gospel since the prologue (1:5: "the light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it") here reaches its acute narrative moment: the agent of darkness leaves the circle of light. From the Evangelist\'s perspective, Judas\'s going out "into the night" is both physical and spiritual — he departs from the one who is the light of the world into the darkness he has chosen.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Judas\'s departure triggers the glorification announcement: "Now the Son of Man is glorified and God is glorified in him." The word "now" (<em>nyn</em>) marks the departure of the betrayer as the beginning of the passion event — the glorification sequence has started. The mutual glorification — Son glorified in God, God glorified in Son — picks up the prayer of 12:28 and anticipates the High Priestly prayer of ch. 17. The Greek structure is a present/aorist: glorification has been set in motion. The Evangelist frames the passion as the definitive glorification event, not despite the death but through it.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"God will glorify the Son in himself, and will glorify him at once" — the immediacy ("at once," <em>euthys</em>) signals that there will be no delay between the crucifixion and the glorification. The Johannine resurrection is not a lengthy deferral of the cross\'s shame; it is the immediate divine reversal that constitutes the glorification. This is consistent with the Fourth Gospel\'s treatment of "lifted up" as a double-meaning term: the lifting on the cross and the lifting in exaltation are aspects of a single event.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The address "My children" (<em>teknia</em>) is unique in the Gospel of John — it appears frequently in 1 John (2:1, 12, 28; 3:7, 18; 4:4; 5:21) but only here in the Gospel. The usage reflects a teacher\'s affectionate address to disciples, not a parent-child biological relationship. The phrase "only a little longer" (<em>mikron</em>) recurs in the farewell discourse (14:19; 16:16–19) as a way of framing the brief interval between the Passion and the resurrection, or between the resurrection and the Parousia, depending on the context. The reference to "where I am going, you cannot come" applies to the Jewish leaders (7:34; 8:21) but is here applied to the disciples too — departure from the kosmos into the Father\'s presence is a journey they will make, but not yet and not by the same means.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"A new commandment I give you: Love one another. As I have loved you, so you must love one another." What makes this commandment "new" (<em>kainē</em>) requires unpacking. The command to love one\'s neighbor was not new — Lev 19:18 was already central to Jewish ethics, and Jesus cites it as the second great commandment in the Synoptics (Mark 12:31). The newness lies in the measure: "as I have loved you." The standard for love is now the cross-shaped love that Jesus has just displayed in the footwashing and is about to display in the passion — a love that serves, suffers, and gives without limit. This is not a quantitative upgrade of Leviticus but a qualitative transformation of what love means by grounding it in the specific shape of Jesus\'s self-giving.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"By this everyone will know that you are my disciples, if you love one another." In the ancient world, groups were identified by their distinctive practices, symbols, and social behaviors. The Qumran community identified themselves by purity, calendar, and communal property; the Pharisees by table fellowship rules and Sabbath practice; the followers of a philosopher by their dress and the opinions they defended in public. Jesus designates mutual love — specifically the kind displayed in the footwashing — as the identity marker of his community. This is a profoundly counter-cultural choice: honor, lineage, and ritual purity were the standard markers of group identity in the first-century Jewish world.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Peter\'s question "Lord, where are you going?" returns to the theme of 13:33 (Jesus going where they cannot follow) and establishes the frame for the farewell discourse that will occupy chs. 14–16. The promise "you will follow later" (<em>husteron de akolouthēseis</em>) carries the implication of martyrdom — a connection Peter\'s tradition made explicit (21:18–19; 2 Pet 1:14). Following Jesus "where he is going" will eventually mean death, as Peter would discover. The answer defers Peter\'s full understanding to a future that, for the disciples, lies on the other side of the resurrection.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Peter\'s declaration "I will lay down my life for you" uses the exact vocabulary of the Good Shepherd discourse (10:11: "the good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep"). Peter is, intentionally or not, offering to do what only the shepherd is described as doing. The irony is Johannine: Peter claims a readiness that he does not yet have. His courage is real but untested; his self-knowledge is inadequate. The declaration is not insincere — the subsequent night\'s events at Gethsemane suggest Peter did draw a sword (18:10) — but the actual test will reveal a gap between intention and capacity.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Jesus\'s final word of the chapter — "Before the rooster crows, you will disown me three times" — transforms Peter\'s confident declaration into a counter-prophecy. The rooster\'s crow in the ancient world marked the third watch of the night (roughly 3 a.m.), often called the <em>gallicinium</em> (cockcrow) in Roman military notation. The triple denial is a socially precise judgment: in the honor-shame culture, public denial of association with someone under threat was the ultimate act of social self-protection. Peter will do exactly what the honor system rewards — protect his own reputation by distancing himself from a condemned man. The chapter closes on this prediction, placing the entire farewell discourse (chs. 14–17) within the shadow of the imminent failure of the one who has just claimed to be most willing to follow.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'john')
    merge_comm(existing, JOHN)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'john', existing)
    print('John 12–13 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
